<div class="comments-body">
<p>Yeah, code generation is great, but I think that, when it's really useful, it's equivalent to creating a "custom language".<br />
That's what Lisp already allow with it's macro system for example.<br />
Other languages have this great feature : Dylan is one on them (it's the one I prefer since Lisp syntax is "Write Once, Read Never" to me).</p>
<span class="comments-post">Posted by <a href="mailto&#58;ybabel&#64;free&#46;fr">YBabel</a> at March 13, 2003 07:38 AM</span>
</div>
<div class="comments-body">
<p>I agree wholeheartedly that the really useful aspects of code generation result from creating a custom problem-domain language.<br />
That said, however, it is generally better to grab the low-hanging fruit when introducing code generation to an organization. Acceptance of the technique is key, and most folks that I show this technique to really need to see a good concrete example before continuing. <br />
This is why we're focusing on the easy stuff first - generation of database schemas and the data access layer of the application. However, once they saw the utility of that approach, they readily came up with other suggestions - in the V2 timeframe, we'll be tackling building business rule abstractions using code generation.</p>
<span class="comments-post">Posted by <a target="_blank" href="http://www.iunknown.com">John Lam</a> at March 13, 2003 09:25 AM</span>
